{"title_page": "U Sports women's volleyball championship", "text_new": "{{Infobox\n| abovestyle = background: #FF322D;\n| above = U Sports women's volleyball championship\n| image = \n| caption = \n| label1 = Sport\n| data1 = [[Indoor volleyball]]\n| label2 = League\n| data2 = [[U Sports]]\n| label3 = First played\n| data3 = 1971\n| label4 = Most recently played\n| data4 = 2019\n| label5 = Current champions\n| data5 = [[UBC Thunderbirds]]\n| label6 = Current runners-up\n| data6 = [[Ryerson Rams]]\n| label7 = Most titles\n| data7 = [[UBC Thunderbirds]] (12)\n}}\nThe '''U Sports women's volleyball championship''' is an annual tournament that features the top eight women's [[volleyball]] teams from among competing Canadian [[List of universities in Canada|universities]] in [[U Sports]]. 11 games are played over a period of three days culminating in a national championship being awarded.<ref name=Regulations>{{cite web|url=https://usports.ca/uploads/hq/Playing_Regs/2019-20/190625_PlayingRegs_Volleyball_%28W%29.pdf|title=Playing Regulations: Women\u2019s Volleyball|date=June 25, 2019|publisher=[[U Sports]]}}</ref> The championship trophy, first awarded in 1977, features a two-wheeled [[Bullock cart|oxcart]], symbolizing the pioneer era on the [[Red River of the North|Red River]] in [[Manitoba]].<ref name=\"U Sports history\">{{cite web|url=https://usports.ca/en/championships/volleyball/f/history|title=U Sports Volleyball Championship History|access-date=January 3, 2020|website=usports.ca|publisher=U Sports}}</ref> The 2019 champions are the [[UBC Thunderbirds]], who have also won the most championships with a total of 12, including six in a row from 2008 to 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://usports.ca/en/championships/volleyball/f/news/2019/03/2230475171/final|title=Gold Medal Game: T-Birds flying again as national champions|date=March 18, 2019|publisher=[[U Sports]]}}</ref> The 2020 championship tournament was cancelled due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=corona>{{cite web|url=https://calgarysun.com/sports/womens-volleyball-nationals-still-a-go-at-u-of-c|title=Women's volleyball nationals cancelled at U of C|date=March 13, 2020|publisher=[[Calgary Sun]]}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:2015 VB Championship.jpg|thumb|The championship trophy awarded to the gold medalists of the tournament.]]\nWhile intercollegiate volleyball had been played in Canada since 1947, championships had been played for conference titles only.<ref name=\"TVB History\">{{cite web|url=https://varsityblues.ca/sports/2019/6/5/varsity-blues-womens-volleyball-history.aspx?id=1816|title=Varsity Blues Women's Volleyball History|publisher=[[Toronto Varsity Blues]]|access-date=January 4, 2020}}</ref> In 1969, the Canadian Women\u2019s Interuniversity Athletic Union (CWIAU) was formed (a precursor to today's U Sports organization) to provide a regulatory body for national competition.<ref name=\"TVB History\"/> For the 1969-1970 season, the [[Calgary Dinos]] were named the first unofficial champions.<ref name=\"U Sports history\"/> The first official champions were the [[Manitoba Bisons]], who were crowned following the 1970-1971 season.<ref name=\"U Sports history\"/> While full historical championship results are not readily available, the championship was initially a [[round-robin tournament]] where the teams with the best records would then play for the championship. This was changed for the 1983 championship when the tournament changed to [[Tournament#Knockout|single-elimination]].<ref name=\"Archive\">{{cite web|url=https://presto-en.usports.ca/championships/wvball/2009-10/files/past_champ_results_wvball.pdf|title=CIS Championship Results|access-date=March 13, 2020|website=usports.ca|publisher=U Sports}}</ref>\n\n==Format==\nThe championship currently consists of an eight-team tournament, with champions from each of the [[U Sports#Members|four conferences]], one host, an additional [[Ontario University Athletics|OUA]] team, and two additional [[Canada West Universities Athletic Association|Canada West]] teams.<ref name=Regulations/> While the berths for the conference champions and host remain consistent year-to-year, the other three invitees can change based on the host's conference and the competitive landscape in U Sports. The championship takes place over three days and features 11 games, with teams seeded 1-8. Teams are ranked by a committee as well as by the ELO ranking used to determine weekly Top 10 rankings nationally.<ref name=Regulations/> Conference champions can be ranked no lower than 6th place. The team ranked 1st plays the 8th ranked team, 2nd plays 7th, 3rd plays 6th, and 4th plays 5th in the quarter-finals. To ensure common rest times, teams are not re-seeded after the first round, so the winner of 1v8 plays the winner of 4v5 and the winner of 2v7 plays the winner of 3v6.<ref name=Regulations/> There is also a [[Third place playoff|consolation bracket]] to determine the third place winner (bronze medalist) and fifth place winner. The gold medal game is the last game played in the tournament.<ref name=Regulations/>\n\n==Results==\n===Round Robin Format (1971\u20131982)===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%; width:62%; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:6%;\"|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12%;\"|Host<br>(City)\n! width=1% rowspan=44 bgcolor=ffffff|\n! colspan=\"3\"|Championship final\n! width=1% rowspan=44 bgcolor=ffffff|\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:4%;\"|Teams\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! style=\"width:14%; background:#eaecf0;\"|Champions\n! width=9%|Score\n! style=\"width:14%; background:#eaecf0;\"|Runners-up\n|- \n|1971\n|[[University of Calgary|Calgary]]<br>([[Calgary|Calgary, AB]])\n|'''[[Manitoba Bisons]]'''\n|''N/A''\n|''N/A''\n|''N/A''\n|- bgcolor=#E8E8F0\n|1972\n|[[Laurentian University|Laurentian]]<br>([[Greater Sudbury|Sudbury, ON]])\n|'''[[Western Ontario Mustangs]]'''\n|''N/A''\n|''N/A''\n|''N/A''\n|- \n|1973\n|[[Acadia Univer