eb.archive.org/web/20060524165051/http://www.colorado.edu/UCB/AcademicAffairs/ArtsSciences/physics/TZD/PageProofs1/ directory of the book].\n* [http://hyperphysics.phy-astr.gsu.edu/hbase/hframe.html All about 3D Schr\u00f6dinger Equation ]\n*Mathematical aspects of Schr\u00f6dinger equations are discussed on the [http://wiki.math.toronto.edu/DispersiveWiki/index.php/Main_Page Dispersive PDE Wiki].\n* [http://www.nanotechnology.hu/online/web-schroedinger/index.html Web-Schr\u00f6dinger: Interactive solution of the 2D time-dependent and stationary Schr\u00f6dinger equation ]\n* [http://behindtheguesses.blogspot.com/2009/06/schrodinger-equation-corrections.html An alternate reasoning behind the Schr\u00f6dinger Equation ]\n* Online software-[http://nanohub.org/resources/3847 Periodic Potential Lab] Solves the time-independent Schr\u00f6dinger equation for arbitrary periodic potentials.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20180926125403/http://www.felderbooks.com/papers/psi.html What Do You Do With a Wavefunction?]\n*[http://www.felderbooks.com/papers/quantum.html The Young Double-Slit Experiment]\n*[https://github.com/LaurentNevou Schrodinger solver in 1, 2 and 3d]\n\n{{Quantum mechanics topics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schrodinger Equation}}\n[[Category:Schr\u00f6dinger equation| ]]\n[[Category:Differential equations]]\n[[Category:Wave mechanics]]\n[[Category:Functions of space and time]]\n", "name_user": "Aditya shukla8", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling errors", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schr%C3%B6dinger_equation"}
{"title_page": "Sandra Lee (chef)", "text_new": "{{short description|American chef}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{For|other people named Sandra Lee|Sandra Lee (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Sandra Lee\n| image        = Sandra Lee 2012 Shankbone.JPG\n| image_size   = \n| caption      = Lee at the [[2012 Time 100]] gala\n| office       = [[First Lady]] of [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| term_label   = ''De facto''\n| term_start   = January 1, 2011\n| term_end     = September 25, 2019\n| predecessor  = [[Michelle Paige Paterson]]\n| successor    = ''Vacant''\n| governor     = [[Andrew Cuomo]]\n| birth_name   = Sandra Lee Christiansen\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1966|7|3}}\n| birth_place  = [[Santa Monica, California|Santa Monica]], [[California]], U.S.\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| other_names  =\n| spouse       = {{marriage|[[Bruce Karatz]]|2001|2005|reason=divorce}}\n| partner      = [[Andrew Cuomo]] (2005\u20132019)\n| education    = [[University of Wisconsin\u2013La Crosse]]<ref name=\"biography.com\" />\n| occupation   = Television personality, author, celebrity chef\n| website      = {{URL|sandralee.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Sandra Lee Christiansen''' (born July 3, 1966)\nIs an Alcoholic. \nthe whole world found this out when she demonstrated her ability as an intellectual when she went on the food network to show her viewers how to make a lush lagoon. During the couse of the receipe she stated she required 2 shots if vodka to then which she poured in about 200ML compared to the 60 she should have. to try and save face she also stated it would be strong. for many years she was considered a meme about alcoholism but in the midst of 2020 coronavirus pandemic she has proven her worth showing that when you are inside doing absolutely nothing for 13 days and counting, that drinking all the time isnt too bad. Plus remember when she tried to float the kiwi on top and it just sunk to the bottom. She is about as sharp as a bowling ball. Phuk that was funny\n\n==Early life==\nChristiansen was born in [[Santa Monica, California]],<ref name=\"biography.com\" /> the daughter of Vicky and Wayne Christiansen. When Sandra was 2, her mother had her and her younger sister Cindy live with their paternal grandmother, Lorraine.<ref name=\"gma-excerpt\" /> By 1972, the girls' parents had divorced; their mother remarried, moving them to [[Sumner, Washington]]. When Lee was 11, her mother divorced for a second time. Lee by this time had three additional siblings, Kimmy, Richie and Johnny. At 15, following a beating by her mother, Lee moved in with her boyfriend, Duane, and on June 30, 1982, left for Wisconsin to live with her father and his girlfriend.<ref name=\"gma-excerpt\" /> She graduated from Onalaska High School in [[Onalaska, Wisconsin]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://onalaskaalumni.com/sandra-lee/|title=Onalaska High School Alumni Association   \u2013  Sandra Lee|work=Onalaska High School Alumni Association}}</ref> and later attended the [[University of Wisconsin-La Crosse]].<ref name=\"gma-excerpt\">{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/Recipes/story?id=3799773&page=1&singlePage=true|title=Excerpt: 'Made From Scratch'|work=[[Good Morning America]]|date=October 31, 2007|publisher=ABC|accessdate=July 12, 2010|archivedate=May 12, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150512170317/http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/Recipes/story?id=3799773&page=1&singlePage=true|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://sandraleepictures.com/press/FC_1107.htm|title=Recipe for Success|journal=Family Circle|date=November 1, 2007|last=Lee|first=Sandra|accessdate=2010-07-12|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716002837/http://sandraleepictures.com/press/FC_1107.htm|archivedate=July 16, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"nyp\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/pagesixmag/issues/20091203/Sandra+Lee+and+Andrew+Cuomo+Love+Story|title=Sandra Lee and Andrew Cuomo: A Love Story|newspaper=Page Six Magazine|publisher=New York Post|location=New York|accessdate=July 12, 2010|last=Karni|first=Annie|date=December 3, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100802023113/http://www.nypost.com/pagesixmag/issues/20091203/Sandra+Lee+and+Andrew+Cuomo+Love+Story|archivedate=August 2, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> She was raised as a [[Seventh-Day Adventist]] and later her family became [[Jehovah's Witness]].<ref name=\"Tablet\">{{Cite web|last=Hoffman  |first= Allison |authorlink=   |title=Semi-Homemade, Totally Jewish - Turns out Sandra Lee converted a decade ago   |publisher=[[The Tablet]]|date=April 5, 2011 |url=http://www.tabletmag.com/scroll/64047/the-jewish-martha-stewart  |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nIn December of her junior year, she left college to live near family in [[Malibu, California]].<ref name=\"gma-excerpt\" /> She later attended a two week recreational course at [[Le Cordon Bleu]] in [[Ottawa|Ottawa, Ontario]], Canada, which she did not finish.<ref name=\"Vogue02222011\">{{cite news|first=Gully|last=Wells|url=http://www.vogue.com/magazine/article/sandra-lee-the-woman-in-white/|title=Sandra Lee: The Woman in White|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|date=February 22, 2011|accessdate=November 24, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121223151013/http://www.vogue.com/magazine/article/sandra-lee-the-woman-in-white/|archivedate=December 23, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn the early 1990s, Lee created a product called \"Sandra Lee Kraft Kurtains\", a home-decorating tool that used a wire rack and sheets or other fabric samples to create decorative drapery. The product was sold via [[infomercial]]s and cable shopping networks. Home-shopping network [[QVC]] hired her as on-air talent; in her first 18 months on the network, Lee sold $20 million worth of products.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.gourmet.com/magazine/2000s/2003/09/goodbye |title=Good-bye To All That|last=Rochlin|first=Margy|magazine=Gourmet|date=September 2003 |publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast}}</ref>\n\n''Semi-Homemade Cooking with Sandra Lee'' premiered on the [[Food Network]] in 2003. Each episode contains an [[handicraft|arts and crafts]] element, in which Lee decorates the table setting in accordance with the theme of the meal that she just prepared. She refers to these as \"tablescapes\". Lee's second Food Network series, ''Sandra's Money Saving Meals'', began airing on May 10, 2009.<ref name=\"fn-bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.foodnetwork.com/chefs/sandra-lee/index.html|title=Sandra Lee|work=Hosts & Chefs|publisher=[[Food Network]]|accessdate=October 12, 2010|year=2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100825054222/http://www.foodnetwork.com/chefs/sandra-lee/index.html|archivedate=August 25, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\nShe has released 25 books, including Sandra Lee ''Semi-Homemade: Cool Kids Cooking'' (October 2006) and a memoir, ''Made From Scratch'', which was released in November 2007.<ref name=\"fn-bio\" /> A magazine based on her show, ''Sandra Lee Semi-Homemade'', was released in 2009.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS125788+17-Feb-2009+PRN20090217|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130201065903/http://www.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS125788+17-Feb-2009+PRN20090217|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 1, 2013|title=Television Star and Best-Selling Author Sandra Lee and Hoffman Media, Launches New Magazine Sandra Lee Semi-Homemade Today|publisher=Hoffman Media|agency=Reuters.com|accessdate=October 12, 2010|date=February 17, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Lee won the [[Daytime Emmy Award]] for Outstanding Lifestyle/Culinary Host for Semi-Homemade Cooking.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/23/daytime-emmys-2012-winners_n_1621807.html|title=Daytime Emmys 2012 Winners Revealed|last=Moore|first=Frazier|date=June 23, 2012|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=2012-09-19}}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2012, she started a new monthly lifestyle magazine in partnership with TV Guide. She is also starring in two new shows: ''Sandra\u2019s Restaurant Remakes'' and ''Sandra Lee\u2019s Taverns, Lounges & Clubs.''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/entertainment/tv/sandra_lee_getting_out_from_behind_VYD2l1irJrfb1ncYsiEZaI|title=Sandra Lee expands empire|last=Shain|first=Michael|work=New York Post|accessdate=2012-09-26}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical response ===\nWhen the ''[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]'' ran a review of Lee's cookbook ''Semi-Homemade Cooking'' that criticized both her recipe and her \"Semi-Homemade\" concept,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/food/92388_chou23.shtml|title=On Food: 'Semi-Homemade' is a halfhearted view of cooking|last=Chou|first=Hsiao-Ching|date=October 23, 2002|newspaper=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]|accessdate=October 12, 2010|publisher=Hearst Seattle Media|location=Seattle, WA}}</ref>\nthe review's author received a response \"that was more impassioned than I anticipated\", with most readers agreeing with the article. However, a number of readers disagreed with the column. One reader wrote, \"Lots of people who don't want to take the time to shred a cup of carrots want to cook a good meal.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/food/95256_chou13.shtml|title=On Food: Column on Sandra Lee really stirred the pot|last=Chou|first=Hsiao-Ching|date=November 13, 2002|newspaper=Seattle Post-Intelligencer|accessdate=October 12, 2010|publisher=Hearst Seattle Media|location=Seattle, WA}}</ref>\n\nKurt Soller, writing for ''[[Newsweek]]'', compared Lee's impact upon television cooking with that of [[Julia Child]], noting that although Lee's show \"is the furthest from Child's methods\", both women \"filled a niche that hasn't yet been explored\".<ref name=\"anti-julia\" />\n\n'''Kwanzaa cake'''\n\nMuch of the criticism of Lee has coalesced around a recipe for \"[[Kwanzaa]] Cake\" that she demonstrated on a 2003 episode of ''Semi-Homemade Cooking with Sandra Lee''. The recipe consisted of [[Angel food cake|angel food]] cake topped with icing, cinnamon, apple pie filling, pumpkin seeds and [[Corn nut|corn nuts]] (all store-bought), with seven Kwanzaa candles then inserted into the cake.<ref>[http://www.avclub.com/article/this-cake-will-make-your-eyeballs-burst-into-flame-25176 This Cake Will Make Your Eyeballs Burst Into Flames], Amelie Gillette ''The Onion AV Club'', March 16, 2009</ref>\n\nFood writer [[Anthony Bourdain]], who was harshly critical of Lee in general, described the video clip of this segment of the show as \"eye searing\" and \"a war crime\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Eat this, Anthony Bourdain!|first=Moriah |last=Balingit|work=McClatchy \u2013 Tribune Business News|location=Washington|date=June 17, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ripping Rant on Food and Restaurant Business; Surly celebrity chef Anthony Bourdain spouts off about his likes, and mostly passionate dislikes, in the eminently entertaining Medium Raw.|first=Colette|last=Bancroft|work=St. Petersburg Times|location=Florida|date=July 7, 2010|page=E2}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last1=Bourdain|first1=Anthony|title=Medium Raw: A Bloody Valentine to the World of Food and the People Who Cook|publisher=Ecco|isbn=978-0-06-171894-6|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/mediumraw00anth}}</ref> The cake was called \"scary\" by the ''[[Houston Chronicle]]'',<ref>{{cite news|title=Celebrity Chefs/Foodies with groupies|first=Mary|last=Vuong|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|location=Texas|date=May 17, 2006|page=1}}</ref> and \"the most ghastly-sounding dish in Lee's culinary repertoire\" by ''Tulsa World''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Perhaps Democrats should taste Sandra Lee's cooking|first=Charlotte|last=Allen|work=[[Tulsa World]]|location=Oklahoma|date=December 5, 2010|page=G.3}}</ref> ''Salon.com'' wrote that the video \"takes pride of place in the pantheon of hilarious culinary disaster videos\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Just how offensive is Sandra Lee's crazy Kwanzaa cake?|date=December 26, 2010|first=Francis|last=Lam|work=Salon.com|url=http://www.salon.com/food/francis_lam/2010/12/26/sandra_lee_kwanzaa_cake_offensive|accessdate=May 12, 2015|archivedate=December 28, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101228232352/https://www.salon.com/food/francis_lam/2010/12/26/sandra_lee_kwanzaa_cake_offensive}}</ref>\n\nCookbook author Denise Vivaldo, who claims to have ghostwritten recipes for many celebrity chefs, wrote a humorous post in ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' in December 2010 stating that she was responsible for the recipe (though she said that the candles were Lee's idea), and apologizing for it. She also wrote that Lee \"has incredibly bad food taste\".<ref>[http://www.eurweb.com/2010/12/woman-behind-sandra-lee%E2%80%99s-%E2%80%98kwanzaa-cake%E2%80%99-explains-debacle/ Woman behind \u2018Sandra Lee Kwanzaa Cake\u2019 Explains Debacle], ''Lee Bailey's EURweb''</ref> A week later, the post was removed after Lee's lawyer threatened legal action.<ref name=\"ravenous\">{{cite news|url=http://nymag.com/news/features/sandra-lee-2011-4/index6.html|title=The Ravenous and Resourceful Sandra Lee|first=Benjamin|last=Wallace|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=March 27, 2011}}</ref> Lee has said this recipe is the only one of hers whose criticism she has taken to heart, and that the recipe was partly due to the Food Network dictating the show's content at the time.<ref name=\"ravenous\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nFrom 2001 to 2005, she was married to [[KB Home]] CEO and philanthropist [[Bruce Karatz]]<ref name=\"Barbaro\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/15/nyregion/15sandralee.html?pagewanted=all|title=A TV Cook\u2019s Next Serving? Cuomo Family Style|last=Barbaro|first=Michael|date=May 14, 2010|accessdate=28 September 2014}}</ref> for whom she converted to Judaism.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Wallace  |first=Benjamin  |title=The Ravenous and Resourceful Sandra Lee   |magazine=[[New York Magazine]]|date=March 27, 2011 |url=http://nymag.com/news/features/sandra-lee-2011-4/index3.html  |quote=By 1999, Lee had become a spokesperson for KB Home, as well as romantically involved with its CEO, Bruce Karatz, who was 21 years her senior. Karatz\u2019s marriage subsequently dissolved, and by 2001, Lee had converted to Judaism and married Karatz at [[Ron Burkle]]\u2019s estate in Beverly Hills.}}</ref><ref name=\"Tablet\" /> In the fall of 2005, Lee entered into a relationship with [[Andrew Cuomo]], who became [[Governor of New York]] in 2011 and which made Lee the state's de facto First Lady. The two shared homes in [[Chappaqua, New York|Chappaqua]] and [[Poughkeepsie, New York|Poughkeepsie]].<ref name=\"nyp\" /><ref name=\"anti-julia\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/210852|title=Sandra Lee: The Anti-Julia|journal=Newsweek|last=Soller|first=Kurt|date=August 6, 2009|accessdate=October 12, 2010}}</ref> On September 25, 2019, the couple announced that they had ended their relationship.<ref name=\"Split\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/25/nyregion/andrew-cuomo-sandra-lee.html|title= Governor Cuomo and Sandra Lee Have Split Up |author1= McKinley, Jesse|work=[[The New York Times]] |date=25 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Cancer===\nLee announced on May 12, 2015, that she had been diagnosed with early-stage [[breast cancer]]. By then she had undergone a [[lumpectomy]], and was scheduled to have a double [[mastectomy]] later in the week. Governor Cuomo was to take some personal time to be with her during and after the surgery.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/tv-personality-sandra-lee-battling-breast-cancer-urges/story?id=30968304| title=TV Personality Sandra Lee Battling Breast Cancer, Urges Women to Be Screened|date=May 12, 2015|work=Good Morning America|accessdate=May 12, 2015|archivedate= May 12, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150512172908/http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/tv-personality-sandra-lee-battling-breast-cancer-urges/story?id=30968304|url-status=live}}</ref> On October 12, 2015, she was rushed to a hospital because of fluid buildup, believed to be a complication of her recovery, and was monitored closely in the next few days. Cuomo had been attending a [[Billy Joel]] concert at [[Nassau Coliseum]], but left and went to the hospital.<ref name=\"Hospital\">{{cite news|url= https://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/sandra-lee-cuomo-girlfriend-rushed-hospital-source-article-1.2315074 |title=Sandra Lee, Cuomo's girlfriend, rushed to hospital: source|work=[[New York Daily News]]|author1= Lovett, Kenneth |author2=Slattery, Denis|date=5 August 2015}}</ref> Lee has been cancer free since mid-2016.<ref name=\"CancerFree\">{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/sandra-lee-reveals-cancer-free/story?id=33942286|title=Sandra Lee Reveals She Is Cancer Free|work=ABC News| author1=Kindelan, Katie| date=22 September 2015}}</ref>\n==Awards and nominations==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- align=\"center\"\n!Year\n!Award\n!Category\n!Work\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n|2012\n|[[Daytime Emmy Award]]\n|Outstanding Lifestyle/Culinary Host\n|''Semi-Homemade Cooking with Sandra Lee''\n|{{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref name=\":0\" />\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.sandralee.com/}}\n* [http://www.foodnetwork.com/chefs/sandra-lee.html Sandra Lee's Food Network Page]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hon}}\n{{succession box|title=[[First Lady|First Lady of New York]]<br />{{small|De facto}}|before=[[Michelle Paige Paterson]]|after=''Vacant''|years=2011\u20132019}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lifestyle/Culinary Show Host}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lee, Sandra}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American television chefs]]\n[[Category:American women writers]]\n[[Category:Andrew Cuomo]]\n[[Category:First Ladies and Gentlemen of New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Food Network chefs]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from Chappaqua, New York]]\n[[Category:People from Sumner, Washington]]\n[[Category:People from Santa Monica, California]]\n[[Category:People with cancer]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:University of Wisconsin\u2013La Crosse alumni]]\n[[Category:Women chefs]]\n[[Category:Women cookbook writers]]\n[[Category:People from Onalaska, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Le Cordon Bleu]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American chef}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{For|other people named Sandra Lee|Sandra Lee (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Sandra Lee\n| image        = Sandra Lee 2012 Shankbone.JPG\n| image_size   = \n| caption      = Lee at the [[2012 Time 100]] gala\n| office       = [[First Lady]] of [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| term_label   = ''De facto''\n| term_start   = January 1, 2011\n| term_end     = September 25, 2019\n| predecessor  = [[Michelle Paige Paterson]]\n| successor    = ''Vacant''\n| governor     = [[Andrew Cuomo]]\n| birth_name   = Sandra Lee Christiansen\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1966|7|3}}\n| birth_place  = [[Santa Monica, California|Santa Monica]], [[California]], U.S.\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| other_names  =\n| spouse       = {{marriage|[[Bruce Karatz]]|2001|2005|reason=divorce}}\n| partner      = [[Andrew Cuomo]] (2005\u20132019)\n| education    = [[University of Wisconsin\u2013La Crosse]]<ref name=\"biography.com\" />\n| occupation   = Television personality, author, celebrity chef\n| website      = {{URL|sandralee.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Sandra Lee Christiansen''' (born July 3, 1966)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/seattle/stories/2007/05/14/tidbits1.html|title=Food Network star Sandra Lee peeled onions as a youth at the Puyallup Fair|last=Payne|first=Patti|newspaper=Puget Sound Business Journal|publisher=American City Business Journals|location=Seattle, WA|date=May 11, 2007|accessdate=October 12, 2010|archivedate=August 6, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140806200808/http://www.bizjournals.com/seattle/stories/2007/05/14/tidbits1.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"biography.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.biography.com/people/sandra-lee--20906429|title=Sandra Lee Biography: Chef, Writer, Television Personality profile|publisher=Biography.com|accessdate=May 12, 2015}}</ref> is an American [[celebrity chef|television chef]] and [[author]]. She is known for her \"Semi-Homemade\" cooking concept, which Lee describes as using 70 percent pre-packaged products and 30 percent fresh items.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Sandra Lee: The Woman in White|url = http://www.vogue.com/865456/sandra-lee-the-woman-in-white/|website = Vogue|accessdate = 2016-01-08|language = en-US}}</ref> As the partner of Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]], she served as [[New York (state)|New York]]'s ''[[de facto]]'' [[First Lady]] from 2011 to 2019, when the couple ended their relationship.\n\n==Early life==\nChristiansen was born in [[Santa Monica, California]],<ref name=\"biography.com\" /> the daughter of Vicky and Wayne Christiansen. When Sandra was 2, her mother had her and her younger sister Cindy live with their paternal grandmother, Lorraine.<ref name=\"gma-excerpt\" /> By 1972, the girls' parents had divorced; their mother remarried, moving them to [[Sumner, Washington]]. When Lee was 11, her mother divorced for a second time. Lee by this time had three additional siblings, Kimmy, Richie and Johnny. At 15, following a beating by her mother, Lee moved in with her boyfriend, Duane, and on June 30, 1982, left for Wisconsin to live with her father and his girlfriend.<ref name=\"gma-excerpt\" /> She graduated from Onalaska High School in [[Onalaska, Wisconsin]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://onalaskaalumni.com/sandra-lee/|title=Onalaska High School Alumni Association   \u2013  Sandra Lee|work=Onalaska High School Alumni Association}}</ref> and later attended the [[University of Wisconsin-La Crosse]].<ref name=\"gma-excerpt\">{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/Recipes/story?id=3799773&page=1&singlePage=true|title=Excerpt: 'Made From Scratch'|work=[[Good Morning America]]|date=October 31, 2007|publisher=ABC|accessdate=July 12, 2010|archivedate=May 12, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150512170317/http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/Recipes/story?id=3799773&page=1&singlePage=true|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://sandraleepictures.com/press/FC_1107.htm|title=Recipe for Success|journal=Family Circle|date=November 1, 2007|last=Lee|first=Sandra|accessdate=2010-07-12|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716002837/http://sandraleepictures.com/press/FC_1107.htm|archivedate=July 16, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"nyp\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/pagesixmag/issues/20091203/Sandra+Lee+and+Andrew+Cuomo+Love+Story|title=Sandra Lee and Andrew Cuomo: A Love Story|newspaper=Page Six Magazine|publisher=New York Post|location=New York|accessdate=July 12, 2010|last=Karni|first=Annie|date=December 3, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100802023113/http://www.nypost.com/pagesixmag/issues/20091203/Sandra+Lee+and+Andrew+Cuomo+Love+Story|archivedate=August 2, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> She was raised as a [[Seventh-Day Adventist]] and later her family became [[Jehovah's Witness]].<ref name=\"Tablet\">{{Cite web|last=Hoffman  |first= Allison |authorlink=   |title=Semi-Homemade, Totally Jewish - Turns out Sandra Lee converted a decade ago   |publisher=[[The Tablet]]|date=April 5, 2011 |url=http://www.tabletmag.com/scroll/64047/the-jewish-martha-stewart  |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nIn December of her junior year, she left college to live near family in [[Malibu, California]].<ref name=\"gma-excerpt\" /> She later attended a two week recreational course at [[Le Cordon Bleu]] in [[Ottawa|Ottawa, Ontario]], Canada, which she did not finish.<ref name=\"Vogue02222011\">{{cite news|first=Gully|last=Wells|url=http://www.vogue.com/magazine/article/sandra-lee-the-woman-in-white/|title=Sandra Lee: The Woman in White|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|date=February 22, 2011|accessdate=November 24, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121223151013/http://www.vogue.com/magazine/article/sandra-lee-the-woman-in-white/|archivedate=December 23, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn the early 1990s, Lee created a product called \"Sandra Lee Kraft Kurtains\", a home-decorating tool that used a wire rack and sheets or other fabric samples to create decorative drapery. The product was sold via [[infomercial]]s and cable shopping networks. Home-shopping network [[QVC]] hired her as on-air talent; in her first 18 months on the network, Lee sold $20 million worth of products.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.gourmet.com/magazine/2000s/2003/09/goodbye |title=Good-bye To All That|last=Rochlin|first=Margy|magazine=Gourmet|date=September 2003 |publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast}}</ref>\n\n''Semi-Homemade Cooking with Sandra Lee'' premiered on the [[Food Network]] in 2003. Each episode contains an [[handicraft|arts and crafts]] element, in which Lee decorates the table setting in accordance with the theme of the meal that she just prepared. She refers to these as \"tablescapes\". Lee's second Food Network series, ''Sandra's Money Saving Meals'', began airing on May 10, 2009.<ref name=\"fn-bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.foodnetwork.com/chefs/sandra-lee/index.html|title=Sandra Lee|work=Hosts & Chefs|publisher=[[Food Network]]|accessdate=October 12, 2010|year=2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100825054222/http://www.foodnetwork.com/chefs/sandra-lee/index.html|archivedate=August 25, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\nShe has released 25 books, including Sandra Lee ''Semi-Homemade: Cool Kids Cooking'' (October 2006) and a memoir, ''Made From Scratch'', which was released in November 2007.<ref name=\"fn-bio\" /> A magazine based on her show, ''Sandra Lee Semi-Homemade'', was released in 2009.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS125788+17-Feb-2009+PRN20090217|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130201065903/http://www.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS125788+17-Feb-2009+PRN20090217|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 1, 2013|title=Television Star and Best-Selling Author Sandra Lee and Hoffman Media, Launches New Magazine Sandra Lee Semi-Homemade Today|publisher=Hoffman Media|agency=Reuters.com|accessdate=October 12, 2010|date=February 17, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Lee won the [[Daytime Emmy Award]] for Outstanding Lifestyle/Culinary Host for Semi-Homemade Cooking.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/23/daytime-emmys-2012-winners_n_1621807.html|title=Daytime Emmys 2012 Winners Revealed|last=Moore|first=Frazier|date=June 23, 2012|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=2012-09-19}}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2012, she started a new monthly lifestyle magazine in partnership with TV Guide. She is also starring in two new shows: ''Sandra\u2019s Restaurant Remakes'' and ''Sandra Lee\u2019s Taverns, Lounges & Clubs.''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/entertainment/tv/sandra_lee_getting_out_from_behind_VYD2l1irJrfb1ncYsiEZaI|title=Sandra Lee expands empire|last=Shain|first=Michael|work=New York Post|accessdate=2012-09-26}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical response ===\nWhen the ''[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]'' ran a review of Lee's cookbook ''Semi-Homemade Cooking'' that criticized both her recipe and her \"Semi-Homemade\" concept,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/food/92388_chou23.shtml|title=On Food: 'Semi-Homemade' is a halfhearted view of cooking|last=Chou|first=Hsiao-Ching|date=October 23, 2002|newspaper=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]|accessdate=October 12, 2010|publisher=Hearst Seattle Media|location=Seattle, WA}}</ref>\nthe review's author received a response \"that was more impassioned than I anticipated\", with most readers agreeing with the article. However, a number of readers disagreed with the column. One reader wrote, \"Lots of people who don't want to take the time to shred a cup of carrots want to cook a good meal.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/food/95256_chou13.shtml|title=On Food: Column on Sandra Lee really stirred the pot|last=Chou|first=Hsiao-Ching|date=November 13, 2002|newspaper=Seattle Post-Intelligencer|accessdate=October 12, 2010|publisher=Hearst Seattle Media|location=Seattle, WA}}</ref>\n\nKurt Soller, writing for ''[[Newsweek]]'', compared Lee's impact upon television cooking with that of [[Julia Child]], noting that although Lee's show \"is the furthest from Child's methods\", both women \"filled a niche that hasn't yet been explored\".<ref name=\"anti-julia\" />\n\n'''Kwanzaa cake'''\n\nMuch of the criticism of Lee has coalesced around a recipe for \"[[Kwanzaa]] Cake\" that she demonstrated on a 2003 episode of ''Semi-Homemade Cooking with Sandra Lee''. The recipe consisted of [[Angel food cake|angel food]] cake topped with icing, cinnamon, apple pie filling, pumpkin seeds and [[Corn nut|corn nuts]] (all store-bought), with seven Kwanzaa candles then inserted into the cake.<ref>[http://www.avclub.com/article/this-cake-will-make-your-eyeballs-burst-into-flame-25176 This Cake Will Make Your Eyeballs Burst Into Flames], Amelie Gillette ''The Onion AV Club'', March 16, 2009</ref>\n\nFood writer [[Anthony Bourdain]], who was harshly critical of Lee in general, described the video clip of this segment of the show as \"eye searing\" and \"a war crime\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Eat this, Anthony Bourdain!|first=Moriah |last=Balingit|work=McClatchy \u2013 Tribune Business News|location=Washington|date=June 17, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ripping Rant on Food and Restaurant Business; Surly celebrity chef Anthony Bourdain spouts off about his likes, and mostly passionate dislikes, in the eminently entertaining Medium Raw.|first=Colette|last=Bancroft|work=St. Petersburg Times|location=Florida|date=July 7, 2010|page=E2}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last1=Bourdain|first1=Anthony|title=Medium Raw: A Bloody Valentine to the World of Food and the People Who Cook|publisher=Ecco|isbn=978-0-06-171894-6|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/mediumraw00anth}}</ref> The cake was called \"scary\" by the ''[[Houston Chronicle]]'',<ref>{{cite news|title=Celebrity Chefs/Foodies with groupies|first=Mary|last=Vuong|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|location=Texas|date=May 17, 2006|page=1}}</ref> and \"the most ghastly-sounding dish in Lee's culinary repertoire\" by ''Tulsa World''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Perhaps Democrats should taste Sandra Lee's cooking|first=Charlotte|last=Allen|work=[[Tulsa World]]|location=Oklahoma|date=December 5, 2010|page=G.3}}</ref> ''Salon.com'' wrote that the video \"takes pride of place in the pantheon of hilarious culinary disaster videos\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Just how offensive is Sandra Lee's crazy Kwanzaa cake?|date=December 26, 2010|first=Francis|last=Lam|work=Salon.com|url=http://www.salon.com/food/francis_lam/2010/12/26/sandra_lee_kwanzaa_cake_offensive|accessdate=May 12, 2015|archivedate=December 28, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101228232352/https://www.salon.com/food/francis_lam/2010/12/26/sandra_lee_kwanzaa_cake_offensive}}</ref>\n\nCookbook author Denise Vivaldo, who claims to have ghostwritten recipes for many celebrity chefs, wrote a humorous post in ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' in December 2010 stating that she was responsible for the recipe (though she said that the candles were Lee's idea), and apologizing for it. She also wrote that Lee \"has incredibly bad food taste\".<ref>[http://www.eurweb.com/2010/12/woman-behind-sandra-lee%E2%80%99s-%E2%80%98kwanzaa-cake%E2%80%99-explains-debacle/ Woman behind \u2018Sandra Lee Kwanzaa Cake\u2019 Explains Debacle], ''Lee Bailey's EURweb''</ref> A week later, the post was removed after Lee's lawyer threatened legal action.<ref name=\"ravenous\">{{cite news|url=http://nymag.com/news/features/sandra-lee-2011-4/index6.html|title=The Ravenous and Resourceful Sandra Lee|first=Benjamin|last=Wallace|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=March 27, 2011}}</ref> Lee has said this recipe is the only one of hers whose criticism she has taken to heart, and that the recipe was partly due to the Food Network dictating the show's content at the time.<ref name=\"ravenous\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nFrom 2001 to 2005, she was married to [[KB Home]] CEO and philanthropist [[Bruce Karatz]]<ref name=\"Barbaro\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/15/nyregion/15sandralee.html?pagewanted=all|title=A TV Cook\u2019s Next Serving? Cuomo Family Style|last=Barbaro|first=Michael|date=May 14, 2010|accessdate=28 September 2014}}</ref> for whom she converted to Judaism.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Wallace  |first=Benjamin  |title=The Ravenous and Resourceful Sandra Lee   |magazine=[[New York Magazine]]|date=March 27, 2011 |url=http://nymag.com/news/features/sandra-lee-2011-4/index3.html  |quote=By 1999, Lee had become a spokesperson for KB Home, as well as romantically involved with its CEO, Bruce Karatz, who was 21 years her senior. Karatz\u2019s marriage subsequently dissolved, and by 2001, Lee had converted to Judaism and married Karatz at [[Ron Burkle]]\u2019s estate in Beverly Hills.}}</ref><ref name=\"Tablet\" /> In the fall of 2005, Lee entered into a relationship with [[Andrew Cuomo]], who became [[Governor of New York]] in 2011 and which made Lee the state's de facto First Lady. The two shared homes in [[Chappaqua, New York|Chappaqua]] and [[Poughkeepsie, New York|Poughkeepsie]].<ref name=\"nyp\" /><ref name=\"anti-julia\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/210852|title=Sandra Lee: The Anti-Julia|journal=Newsweek|last=Soller|first=Kurt|date=August 6, 2009|accessdate=October 12, 2010}}</ref> On September 25, 2019, the couple announced that they had ended their relationship.<ref name=\"Split\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/25/nyregion/andrew-cuomo-sandra-lee.html|title= Governor Cuomo and Sandra Lee Have Split Up |author1= McKinley, Jesse|work=[[The New York Times]] |date=25 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Cancer===\nLee announced on May 12, 2015, that she had been diagnosed with early-stage [[breast cancer]]. By then she had undergone a [[lumpectomy]], and was scheduled to have a double [[mastectomy]] later in the week. Governor Cuomo was to take some personal time to be with her during and after the surgery.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/tv-personality-sandra-lee-battling-breast-cancer-urges/story?id=30968304| title=TV Personality Sandra Lee Battling Breast Cancer, Urges Women to Be Screened|date=May 12, 2015|work=Good Morning America|accessdate=May 12, 2015|archivedate= May 12, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150512172908/http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/tv-personality-sandra-lee-battling-breast-cancer-urges/story?id=30968304|url-status=live}}</ref> On October 12, 2015, she was rushed to a hospital because of fluid buildup, believed to be a complication of her recovery, and was monitored closely in the next few days. Cuomo had been attending a [[Billy Joel]] concert at [[Nassau Coliseum]], but left and went to the hospital.<ref name=\"Hospital\">{{cite news|url= https://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/sandra-lee-cuomo-girlfriend-rushed-hospital-source-article-1.2315074 |title=Sandra Lee, Cuomo's girlfriend, rushed to hospital: source|work=[[New York Daily News]]|author1= Lovett, Kenneth |author2=Slattery, Denis|date=5 August 2015}}</ref> Lee has been cancer free since mid-2016.<ref name=\"CancerFree\">{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/sandra-lee-reveals-cancer-free/story?id=33942286|title=Sandra Lee Reveals She Is Cancer Free|work=ABC News| author1=Kindelan, Katie| date=22 September 2015}}</ref>\n==Awards and nominations==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- align=\"center\"\n!Year\n!Award\n!Category\n!Work\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n|2012\n|[[Daytime Emmy Award]]\n|Outstanding Lifestyle/Culinary Host\n|''Semi-Homemade Cooking with Sandra Lee''\n|{{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref name=\":0\" />\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.sandralee.com/}}\n* [http://www.foodnetwork.com/chefs/sandra-lee.html Sandra Lee's Food Network Page]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hon}}\n{{succession box|title=[[First Lady|First Lady of New York]]<br />{{small|De facto}}|before=[[Michelle Paige Paterson]]|after=''Vacant''|years=2011\u20132019}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lifestyle/Culinary Show Host}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lee, Sandra}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American television chefs]]\n[[Category:American women writers]]\n[[Category:Andrew Cuomo]]\n[[Category:First Ladies and Gentlemen of New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Food Network chefs]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from Chappaqua, New York]]\n[[Category:People from Sumner, Washington]]\n[[Category:People from Santa Monica, California]]\n[[Category:People with cancer]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:University of Wisconsin\u2013La Crosse alumni]]\n[[Category:Women chefs]]\n[[Category:Women cookbook writers]]\n[[Category:People from Onalaska, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Le Cordon Bleu]]\n", "name_user": "KylfaFroknulf", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sandra_Lee_(chef)"}
